				<p>
				<b>Introduction</b></p>
				<p class="body">
				<img border="1" src="../../../contrib/myKnickKnacks/0_img/08302003-J&W-Acoma-032.jpg" width="150" height="190" align="left" hspace="10" vspace="10">My 
				first encounter with the Goodell-Pratt Co. name happened years 
				ago.&nbsp; I was just developing my interest in vintage tools 
				and eBay offered opportunity to see large numbers of them.&nbsp; 
				At the time the esthetics of the tools was the only criteria I 
				could apply, since I didn’t know anything else about them.&nbsp; 
				The Goodell-Pratt hand drill No. 5.5 looked very interesting to 
				me and it was the first drill I purchased.</p>
				<p class="body">
				Since then I have seen many drills made by the Goodell-Pratt Co. 
				and questions about the name often picked my interest.&nbsp; Who 
				were Goodell and Pratt?&nbsp; The answer to these questions did 
				not come easy. </p>
				<p class="body">
				Some years went by and first clue came with a short but potent 
				article titled “Sorting Out the Goodell Companies” by Ken Cope, 
				published in EAIA’s Chronicle in December, 1992. Shortly after I 
				found a book by Paul Jenkins titled “The Conservative Rebel”, 
				published in 1982 by The Town of Greenfield, MA, and it opened 
				my eyes. With every next bit of information the facts began fall 
				into proper place and the picture emerged.</p>
				<p class="body">
				Several other sources were helpful.&nbsp; Internet played the 
				most important role for me and without it, the following article 
				would not be possible.&nbsp; Websites like “<a target="_blank" href="http://www.oldtoolheaven.com/index.html">A 
				Millers Falls Home Page</a>”, &quot;<a target="_blank" href="http://www.georgesbasement.com/">George's 
				Basement</a>&quot;, and “<a target="_blank" href="http://www.sydnassloot.com/index.htm">Sydnas 
				Sloot</a>” were helpful in creating overall picture of events 
				related to the Goodell-Pratt Co.&nbsp; Other sources, especially 
				websites with hard historical data, were the most valuable 
				source of information.</p>
				<p class="body">
				Although today it is possible to find more information about the 
				Goodell-Pratt Co. and its founders, there is still lack of 
				in-depth information about Goodell brothers.&nbsp; It feels as 
				if the reporters of history did not and still do not give them 
				well deserved recognition and properly emphasize their 
				contribution to the development of very important companies.</p>
				<p class="body">
				In my view

				<font SIZE="2">

				Goodell brothers</font>
				were the real nucleus of the Goodell-Pratt Co. and essential 
				contributors to the growth of the Millers Falls Co.&nbsp; The 
				history of their life and achievements deserve thorough report 
				and this article is an attempt to provide just that.</p>
